explanation.body:
\textbf{\underline{A. Taurine / hydrolysis / protease:}}
\indent[1rem]{- Taurine is a component of bile salts, but cholesterol is the primary starting material.}
\indent[1rem]{- Hydrolysis is a general term for breaking down molecules with water.}
\indent[1rem]{- Protease is an enzyme that breaks down proteins, not fats.}

\textbf{\underline{B. Triglycerides / agglomeration / amylase:}}
\indent[1rem]{- Triglycerides are fats themselves, not a source for bile salts.}
\indent[1rem]{- Agglomeration means clumping together, while emulsification is the opposite, breaking down large particles.}
\indent[1rem]{- Amylase is an enzyme that breaks down carbohydrates, not fats.}

\textbf{\underline{C. Bilirubin / micelles formation / salivary lipase:}}
\indent[1rem]{- Bilirubin is a waste product, not a component of bile salts.}
\indent[1rem]{- Micelle formation is a correct term for the structures formed by bile salts and fat particles, but happens later in the process.}
\indent[1rem]{- Salivary lipase does fat digestion in the mouth, but pancreatic lipase is the major player in the small intestine.}

\textbf{\underline{D. Cholesterol / emulsification / pancreatic lipase:}}
\indent[1rem]{- Cholesterol is the starting material for bile salts produced by the liver.}
\indent[1rem]{- Emulsification is the process by which bile salts break down large fat globules into smaller particles.}
\indent[1rem]{- Pancreatic lipase is the key enzyme that breaks down these emulsified fats.}
